h names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Clopton was born about 1387, in Clopton, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Clopton, was 39 and his mother, Mary de Charlton, was 34. He married Alice de Besford in 1402, in Besford, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died on 7 September 1419, in Besford, Worcestershire, England, at the age of 33, and was buried in Quinton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1387–7 September 1419":"umbes 1387–7. september 1419","1387–1419":"1387–1419","1386–1430":"1386–1430","1403–Male":"1403–Surnud","1405–1435":"1405–1435","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1350–1384":"1350–1384","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1384":"1384","1350":"1350","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1435":"1435","1379":"1379","about 1405":"umbes 1405","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1387":"1387","about 1403":"umbes 1403","1430":"1430","1386":"1386","about 1387":"umbes 1387","7 September 1419":"7. september 1419","1419":"1419","1405":"1405","Quinton, Stratford-on-Avon District, Warwickshire, England":"Quinton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Clopton, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","Besford, Worcestershire, England":"Besford, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1387–7 September 1419":"noin 1387–7. syyskuuta 1419","1387–1419":"1387